            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "You can think of `sum`, `mean`, `max`, and `min` as reduction operations. They reduce many values down to fewer values. Reductions are common in machine learning because a model often produces many per-example numbers, and then a loss function reduces them to one scalar objective."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Autograd becomes important once a tensor represents something trainable, such as a weight. When `requires_grad=True`, PyTorch remembers the operations used to produce a result. After you call `backward()`, PyTorch fills `.grad` on the leaf tensors that need updates."},
