            {"type": "code", "title": "Polynomial gradient example", "content": "x = torch.tensor(3.0, requires_grad=True)\nf = x**2 + 2*x + 10\nprint(f)           # 25.0\nprint(f.grad_fn)   # something like <AddBackward0 ...>\nf.backward()\nprint(x.grad)      # 8.0"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "In that example, `grad_fn` means the current tensor was produced by some differentiable operation. PyTorch stores the local backward rule for each operation node. When you call `backward()`, PyTorch chains those local rules together using the chain rule from calculus."},
