            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Now look at a chain-rule example. Let `z = tan(log(x^3 y^3 + xy + y^2 x))`. That expression looks intimidating, but the idea is still the same: break it into intermediate pieces and differentiate one step at a time."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Breaking a complex expression into steps", "content": "a = x**3 * y**3\nb = x * y\nc = y**2 * x\nu = a + b + c\nv = log(u)\nz = tan(v)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Once you define intermediates, the graph becomes easier to read. `z` depends on `v`. `v` depends on `u`. `u` depends on `a`, `b`, and `c`. And those depend on `x` and `y`. Autograd stores this graph automatically while your code runs forward."},
